I have a `users` table which is populated by `CakeDC/Users`, and I need to have support for 3 types of users (this won&#39;t change for the upcoming future): admins, fighters and referees. Since I want to keep `users` pure incase there are CakeDC field updates I decided to create a &quot;profiles&quot; table named `my_users` which belongsTo `users` and the 3 extending tables will use `users.role` and `users.is_superuser` to determine if the user is an admin, fighter or referee.

So to summarize, my Table/plugin setup is:

- `vendor/users/src/Model/Table/UsersTable` which is the core CakeDC/users table.

- `plugins/MyUsers/src/Model/Table/MyUsersTable` which defines base validation rules shared by admins, referees and fighters.

- `plugins/Fighters/src/Model/Table/FightersTable` which extends MyUsersTable and I can define specific validation rules for each.
- `plugins/Referees/src/Model/Table/FightersTable` and `plugins/Admins/src/Model/Table/AdminsTable`, same as the above

To differentiate between the different users, I&#39;ve established a `beforeFind` on `MyUsersTable` which innerJoins to users based on the respective table&#39;s `ROLE` class constant.

MyUsersTable.php:

    class MyUsersTable extends Table
    {   
        public function initialize(array $config)
        {
            parent::initialize($config);
    
            $this-&gt;setTable(&#39;my_users&#39;);
        
            $this-&gt;setPrimaryKey(&#39;user_id&#39;);
    
            $this-&gt;belongsTo(&#39;Users&#39;, [
                &#39;className&#39; =&gt; &#39;Users.Users&#39;,
                &#39;foreignKey&#39; =&gt; &#39;user_id&#39;,
            ]);
        }
    
        /**
         * @param Cake\Event\Event $event
         * @param Cake\ORM\Query $query
         * @param ArrayObject $options
         */
        public function beforeFind(Event $event, Query $query, \ArrayObject $options)
    {
            $and = [];

            // set superuser
            if (defined(static::class.&#39;::IS_ADMIN&#39;) &amp;&amp; static::IS_ADMIN) {
                $and[&#39;is_superuser&#39;] = 1;
            }

            // set the role
            if (defined(static::class.&#39;::ROLE&#39;) &amp;&amp; mb_strlen(static::ROLE) &gt; 0) {
                $and[&#39;role&#39;] = static::ROLE;
            }

            // set user conditions
            $query-&gt;innerJoinWith(&#39;Users&#39;, function($query) use($and) {
                return $query-&gt;andWhere($and);
            });
        }

        /**
         * @param \Cake\ORM\Query $query
         * @param array $options
         */
        public function findByRegistrationCode(Query $query, array $options): Query
        {
            $query-&gt;where([
                $this-&gt;aliasField(&#39;registration_no&#39;) =&gt; $options[&#39;registration_no&#39;]
            ]);
        
            return $query;
        }
    }

And FightersTable.php:

    use MyUsers\Model\Table\MyUsers;
        
    class FightersTable extends MyUsersTable
    {       
        const ROLE = &#39;fighter&#39;;
            
        public function initialize(array $config)
        {   
            parent::initialize($config);
            
            $this-&gt;setEntityClass(&#39;Fighters\Model\Entity\Fighter&#39;);
        }       
            
        /**
         * @param Validator $validator
         * @return Validator $validator
         */
        public function validationDefault(Validator $validator): Validator
        {
            $validator = parent::validationDefault($validator);
    
            $validator-&gt;allowEmpty(&#39;field&#39;);
        }
    }

With `FightersTable` and Referees/Admins, you can see that I establish a role class constant which is used in `MyUsers::beforeFind`. I also define separate entity models in initialize.

So far the &quot;gotchas&quot; have been that:

1. I need to use `$this-&gt;aliasField` in `MyUsers` so this can work reliably without throwing an ambiguous column because Cake tries to map/distinguish due to `FightersTable` extending `MyUsers`.
2. If I need to do an entity pull within `MyUsersTable` and I want to reference just the `MyUsersTable` itself, I need to call `TableRegistry::get(&#39;MyUsers.MyUsers&#39;)` because $this would make this dynamically work with `Drivers` and apply the beforeFind condition.

My question/concerns given this setup:

1. Is there a more &quot;cake&quot; way of accomplishing this without creating separate tables for Referees/Fighters/Admins? Originally I had just `MyUsers` and finders for the 3 user types, but the class became a little messy and in my opinion, this approach is cleaner. 
2. Can I avoid gotcha #1 or gotcha #2 at all?
3. Any restrictions or can there be any optimizations with this setup? I don&#39;t foresee more than 400 users in the next 2 years so hoping the innerJoinWith Users on the beforeFind isn&#39;t too bad because the `role` exists in `users` and moving it would cause redundancy.

